    title: 'Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) Architecture',
    content: 'Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) enhances AI agent responses by grounding them in external knowledge retrieved at query time. The standard RAG pipeline consists of three stages: indexing, retrieval, and generation. During indexing, source documents are chunked (typically 256-1024 tokens), embedded using models like OpenAI text-embedding-3-small or Cohere embed-v3, and stored in a vector database such as Pinecone, Weaviate, Qdrant, or pgvector. At query time, the user question is embedded using the same model, a similarity search retrieves the top-k most relevant chunks (usually k=3-10), and these chunks are injected into the LLM prompt as context for generation. Advanced RAG strategies include hybrid search combining dense vector similarity with sparse BM25 keyword matching, re-ranking retrieved chunks using cross-encoder models, query expansion that reformulates the original question to improve recall, and hierarchical retrieval that first identifies relevant documents then searches within them. Chunking strategy significantly impacts quality: naive fixed-size chunking often splits semantic units, while recursive character splitting, sentence-based chunking, or semantic chunking that detects topic boundaries produce more coherent chunks. Metadata filtering allows narrowing retrieval by document type, date, department, or access level before vector similarity is computed. For agents, RAG enables dynamic knowledge access without fine-tuning, supports knowledge updates without retraining, and provides citation traceability. Key metrics for RAG evaluation include retrieval precision and recall, answer faithfulness (does the response accurately reflect retrieved context), and answer relevance (does the response address the query). Production RAG systems should implement chunk deduplication, staleness detection, and feedback loops where user ratings improve retrieval quality over time.',
