    title: 'Temperature and Sampling Parameters for Agents',
    content: 'Temperature and sampling parameters control the randomness and creativity of AI agent outputs, and choosing appropriate values is critical for reliable agent behavior. Temperature scales the logit distribution before sampling: a temperature of 0.0 always selects the highest-probability token (greedy decoding), while higher temperatures flatten the distribution and increase randomness. For production agents, temperature selection depends on the task type. Deterministic tasks like data extraction, classification, structured output generation, and compliance checking should use temperature 0.0-0.2 for maximum consistency. Semi-creative tasks like customer support responses, email drafting, and explanations work well at 0.3-0.5. Highly creative tasks like marketing copy, brainstorming, and content generation benefit from 0.6-0.8. Temperatures above 0.9 are rarely appropriate for agents as they introduce too much randomness. Top-p (nucleus) sampling provides an alternative control by limiting sampling to the smallest set of tokens whose cumulative probability exceeds the threshold p. A top-p of 0.9 considers only tokens in the top 90% probability mass, filtering out unlikely tokens. Top-p and temperature can be used together, though many practitioners set one and use defaults for the other. Frequency penalty and presence penalty reduce repetition: frequency penalty reduces the probability of tokens proportional to how often they have appeared, while presence penalty applies a flat reduction to any token that has appeared at all. For agents that generate structured outputs like JSON, very low temperature (0.0-0.1) with strict output format instructions minimizes parsing errors. When running evaluation benchmarks, always use temperature 0.0 for reproducibility. Some model providers support seed parameters for deterministic outputs at a given temperature, which is valuable for regression testing.',
