    title: 'AI Credit Risk Assessment',
    content: 'AI-powered credit risk assessment leverages machine learning to evaluate borrower creditworthiness with greater accuracy and speed than traditional scoring models. Traditional credit scoring relies heavily on credit bureau data and simple logistic regression models, while AI approaches incorporate alternative data sources and complex non-linear relationships. Alternative data for credit scoring includes bank transaction history (income stability, spending patterns, savings behavior), utility and rent payment records, e-commerce and digital footprint data, mobile phone usage patterns, and social media activity (subject to ethical and regulatory constraints). Machine learning models used in credit risk include gradient boosting machines (XGBoost, LightGBM) which typically outperform logistic regression by 5-15% in terms of AUC-ROC, random forests for robust ensemble predictions, neural networks for capturing complex non-linear relationships, and survival analysis models for predicting time-to-default. Model development must address bias and fairness: the US Equal Credit Opportunity Act (ECOA) and EU non-discrimination directives prohibit credit decisions based on protected characteristics including race, gender, national origin, and religion. Disparate impact analysis tests whether model outcomes disproportionately affect protected groups even when protected attributes are not direct inputs. Techniques for bias mitigation include pre-processing methods that balance training data, in-processing constraints that penalize discriminatory predictions, and post-processing calibration that adjusts score thresholds across groups. Model explainability requirements under the US Fair Credit Reporting Act mandate that adverse action notices provide specific reasons for credit denial. SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) values and LIME (Local Interpretable Model-agnostic Explanations) provide feature-level explanations for individual predictions. Model monitoring in production must track population stability index (PSI) for input drift, model performance degradation over time, and systematic bias emergence across demographic segments.',
