    title: 'Audit Trail Requirements for Financial AI',
    content: 'Financial AI systems must maintain comprehensive audit trails that document every automated decision, data access, and system action to satisfy regulatory examination requirements, support dispute resolution, and enable forensic investigation. Regulatory frameworks mandating audit trails include SOX Section 404 for US public companies requiring documentation of internal controls over financial reporting, Basel III operational risk requirements for banks, MiFID II for investment firms requiring order and transaction record keeping, and SAMA requirements for financial institutions in Saudi Arabia. An effective audit trail for financial AI captures the complete decision chain: input data received, features computed, model version used, confidence score generated, decision rule applied, action taken, and any human override with justification. For transaction monitoring systems, each alert must record the triggering transaction details, detection rule or model that fired, risk score and contributing factors, investigation steps taken, and final disposition with supporting rationale. Data lineage tracking traces every data element from its original source through all transformations to its final use in model inputs, ensuring that data quality issues can be traced and corrected. Immutability is a core requirement: audit records must be append-only and protected against modification or deletion, typically achieved through write-once-read-many storage, cryptographic hashing, or blockchain-based logging. Retention periods vary by regulation and jurisdiction: SOX requires 7 years for audit workpapers, AML regulations typically require 5 years after the business relationship ends, and MiFID II requires 5-7 years for transaction records. Access to audit trails should be restricted through role-based access controls, with access itself being logged. Automated monitoring should alert on unusual patterns in audit records such as bulk deletions, timestamp gaps, or high volumes of manual overrides that might indicate control failures or fraudulent activity.',
