    title: 'AI Contract Law and Liability',
    content: 'The legal framework governing AI contracts addresses liability allocation, warranty provisions, performance guarantees, and intellectual property rights in an evolving regulatory landscape. AI service contracts must clearly define several critical elements: scope of AI capabilities and limitations, performance metrics with measurable thresholds (accuracy rates, uptime SLAs, response latency), data rights specifying ownership and usage permissions for training data, input data, and output data, and liability allocation for AI errors or harmful outputs. Warranty provisions for AI systems differ from traditional software warranties because AI output quality is probabilistic rather than deterministic. Contracts should specify accuracy benchmarks, define how accuracy is measured, and establish remediation procedures when performance degrades below thresholds. Limitation of liability clauses must address both direct damages from AI errors and consequential damages from decisions made based on AI outputs. Indemnification provisions should cover intellectual property infringement claims (AI outputs infringing third-party copyrights or patents), data breach liability, regulatory fines resulting from AI non-compliance, and third-party claims arising from AI-generated advice or decisions. The emerging legal concept of AI vicarious liability attributes the actions of an AI system to the entity that deployed it, similar to employer liability for employee actions. Force majeure clauses should explicitly address AI-specific risks including model provider API changes, training data poisoning, and adversarial attacks. For SaaS-based AI services, subscription agreements must address data residency requirements, subprocessor management, and cross-border data transfer mechanisms. Insurance products for AI liability are emerging, with policies covering professional liability for AI-generated advice, cyber liability for data breaches, and errors and omissions for AI system failures. Dispute resolution clauses should specify mechanisms for resolving disagreements over AI performance measurement.',
