    title: 'Intellectual Property and AI',
    content: 'The intersection of AI and intellectual property law presents unresolved questions around ownership of AI-generated outputs, copyright in training data, and patent eligibility for AI inventions. Copyright law in most jurisdictions requires human authorship for copyright protection: the US Copyright Office has ruled that works generated entirely by AI without meaningful human creative control are not copyrightable, as affirmed in the Thaler v. Perlmutter decision. However, works created with AI assistance where a human makes creative choices in prompting, selecting, and arranging may qualify for protection of the human-contributed elements. The EU AI Act and member state copyright laws are developing frameworks for AI-generated works. Training data copyright remains contentious: the Authors Guild v. OpenAI and New York Times v. Microsoft lawsuits challenge whether using copyrighted works to train AI models constitutes fair use or requires licensing. The EU Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market (Article 4) provides a text and data mining exception for research organizations and permits commercial mining unless rights holders have expressly reserved their rights. Patent law faces similar authorship questions: the DABUS cases across multiple jurisdictions tested whether an AI system can be named as an inventor, with most jurisdictions (US, UK, EU) ruling that patents require a natural person as inventor. However, patents on AI-assisted inventions where a human directs the AI and applies its outputs remain valid. Trade secret protection for AI models, training data, and proprietary prompts is increasingly important, requiring organizations to implement confidentiality measures, access controls, and contractual protections. Open source AI licenses like Apache 2.0, MIT, and the newer Responsible AI Licenses (RAIL) define how AI models and their outputs may be used, modified, and distributed. Organizations should establish clear IP policies addressing AI-generated content ownership, training data sourcing and licensing, and output attribution requirements.',
