    content: 'AI in employment contexts, particularly hiring, is subject to increasing legal scrutiny as regulators address algorithmic bias and discrimination. New York City Local Law 144, effective July 2023, is the first US law specifically regulating automated employment decision tools (AEDTs), requiring annual bias audits by independent auditors that test for disparate impact across race/ethnicity and gender categories, public posting of audit results, and candidate notification with option to request alternative processes. The EU AI Act classifies AI systems used in employment, worker management, and access to self-employment as high-risk (Annex III), requiring conformity assessments, risk management systems, data governance, transparency to affected persons, human oversight, and accuracy/robustness testing. The US Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) has issued guidance clarifying that existing Title VII and ADA protections apply to AI hiring tools: employers are liable for discriminatory outcomes from AI systems even when provided by third-party vendors. The EEOC identifies specific risks including AI screening tools that disproportionately exclude candidates with disabilities who cannot complete video interviews or personality assessments, resume screening algorithms trained on historically biased hiring data perpetuating past discrimination, and chatbot interviews that penalize non-native English speakers or neurodivergent communication styles. The Illinois Artificial Intelligence Video Interview Act requires consent before AI analyzes video interviews and mandates data deletion upon request. The UK Equality Act 2010 prohibits indirect discrimination that could result from algorithmic bias, and the ICO has issued guidance on AI in recruitment. Best practices for legally compliant AI hiring include conducting disparate impact analysis using the four-fifths rule before deployment, maintaining detailed documentation of AI system development, validation, and monitoring, providing reasonable accommodations including alternative assessment methods, and ensuring human review of AI-assisted decisions at key stages.',
