    content: 'AI-powered contract review identifies risks, anomalies, and unfavorable terms that might be overlooked in manual review of complex agreements. Red flag detection covers several categories of contractual risk. Liability and indemnification red flags include unlimited liability exposure, one-sided indemnification obligations, broad indemnification scope covering consequential and indirect damages, and missing liability caps or insurance requirements. Termination clause red flags include automatic renewal with narrow cancellation windows, penalties for early termination exceeding reasonable liquidated damages, termination for convenience granted only to one party, and missing cure periods for breach-based termination. Intellectual property red flags include overly broad IP assignment clauses that capture pre-existing IP, work-for-hire provisions inconsistent with the engagement type, non-compete clauses with unreasonable geographic or temporal scope, and missing IP indemnification from the provider. Data and privacy red flags include broad data usage rights beyond the stated purpose, missing data breach notification obligations, inadequate data security commitments, and cross-border data transfer without appropriate safeguards. Payment term red flags include net-90 or longer payment windows, missing late payment interest provisions, price escalation clauses without caps or benchmarks, and audit rights with unreasonable access scope. AI contract review systems use NLP to extract and classify contractual provisions, compare terms against organizational standard positions and market benchmarks, and generate risk scores with specific clause-level recommendations. The technology leverages named entity recognition for party identification, clause classification models trained on large contract corpora, and semantic similarity matching against playbook positions. Implementation should include a human-in-the-loop review stage where legal professionals validate AI findings, as AI may miss context-dependent risks or industry-specific implications.',
