    content: 'The Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB) establishes auditing standards for public company audits in the United States, directly impacting how AI tools can be used in audit engagements. PCAOB AS 1001 defines responsibilities and functions of the independent auditor, requiring professional skepticism and due professional care that cannot be fully delegated to AI systems. AS 2201 governs the audit of internal control over financial reporting (integrated with a financial statement audit), requiring the auditor to plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether material weaknesses exist. AI tools supporting ICFR audits can automate control testing by analyzing complete transaction populations rather than samples, identifying anomalies that indicate control failures, and mapping process flows to identify segregation of duties violations. AS 2110 on identifying and assessing risks of material misstatement requires understanding the entity and its environment, which AI can support through automated financial ratio analysis, industry benchmarking, and trend identification. AS 2301 on the auditor responses to assessed risks requires audit procedures whose nature, timing, and extent address identified risks, and AI enables continuous auditing approaches that test all transactions throughout the period rather than sampling at a point in time. AS 2810 on evaluating audit results requires the auditor to evaluate whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement, which AI supports through comprehensive variance analysis and predictive modeling. PCAOB inspection findings have highlighted that AI usage in audit must be accompanied by appropriate auditor skill, knowledge, and oversight, with the auditor responsible for understanding the methodology and assessing the reliability of AI-generated results. Current PCAOB guidance emphasizes that while AI tools can enhance audit quality and efficiency, they do not reduce the auditor responsibility for professional judgment and the sufficiency and appropriateness of audit evidence.',
