    title: 'SOX Compliance and AI',
    content: 'The Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 (SOX) mandates internal control requirements for US public companies that significantly impact how AI systems are deployed in financial reporting processes. Section 302 requires CEO and CFO certification of financial statements and disclosure controls, making executives personally accountable for AI systems that contribute to financial reporting. Section 404 requires management assessment and external audit of internal controls over financial reporting (ICFR), meaning that AI systems involved in financial transaction processing, reconciliation, or reporting become in-scope controls that must be documented, tested, and evaluated. AI-specific SOX considerations include IT General Controls (ITGCs) over AI systems: change management for model updates and prompt changes, access controls limiting who can modify AI configurations, program development controls ensuring AI systems are properly tested before deployment, and computer operations controls ensuring AI system availability and data integrity. Application controls within AI systems include input validation that ensures data quality, processing controls that verify calculation accuracy, and output controls that confirm report completeness. When AI automates previously manual controls, the nature of testing changes from inquiry and observation to inspection of system configurations and data analysis. Documentation requirements under SOX include flowcharts of processes where AI is involved, risk and control matrices mapping AI controls to financial statement assertions, and test plans that validate AI control effectiveness. SOX Section 409 requires real-time disclosure of material events, and AI monitoring systems that detect such events must themselves be subject to SOX controls. Management assessment of AI control effectiveness requires evaluating design effectiveness (is the AI control properly designed to prevent or detect misstatement) and operating effectiveness (did the AI control operate consistently throughout the reporting period). Deficiency classification follows the PCAOB hierarchy of control deficiency, significant deficiency, and material weakness.',
