    content: 'Government procurement of AI systems requires frameworks that ensure value for money, fairness, transparency, and responsible AI deployment with public funds. The WTO Government Procurement Agreement (GPA) and national procurement regulations establish baseline requirements for competitive, transparent procurement processes. AI-specific procurement challenges include difficulty in defining requirements for probabilistic systems, evaluating vendor claims about AI capabilities, assessing long-term costs including model updates and retraining, and managing vendor lock-in risks with proprietary AI systems. The UK Government Digital Service (GDS) guidelines for AI procurement recommend starting with the problem not the technology, assessing whether AI is the appropriate solution, requiring algorithmic impact assessments, mandating transparency about AI use, and ensuring ongoing monitoring and evaluation budgets. The US Executive Order on AI (October 2023) requires federal agencies to designate Chief AI Officers, conduct AI risk assessments, complete AI use case inventories, and establish AI governance structures that influence procurement decisions. Evaluation criteria for AI procurement should include technical capability demonstrated through proof-of-concept testing, data governance and privacy compliance, bias testing and fairness documentation, explainability and transparency features, vendor financial stability and support capacity, and total cost of ownership over the contract lifecycle. Contract structures for AI procurement should address data ownership and portability, model performance guarantees with measurement mechanisms, continuous improvement obligations and retraining schedules, exit provisions including data export and transition support, liability allocation for AI errors affecting citizens, and compliance with evolving AI regulations. Best practices include pilot programs before full deployment, independent testing and validation of vendor AI systems, multi-vendor strategies to avoid concentration risk, and building internal government AI expertise to serve as informed buyers.',
